<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;Elves seldom give unguarded advice, for advice is a dangerous gift, even from the wise to the wise, and all courses may run ill.&quot; - Gildor (LOTR: FOTR)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEB887><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=heartjoys>heartjoys</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><font color=purple><b>Velvet-Steel Wannabe</b></font></span><br>  Posts: 1669<br> <font color=#B87333>(11/7/03 7:20 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=56.topic&index=1>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://heartjoys.fcpages.com/CladdaghAward.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Praying for the dead</span><hr size=1> This is common in Orthodoxy; death is no defeat for the Christian, those who die in the Lord Jesus Christ.  They still remain a vital part of the Church and the Body of Christ.<br>
<br>
Information on Orthodoxy published by <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Conciliar Press</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> says this:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>  [those who have died in the Lord] are alive in the Lord and &quot;registered in heaven&quot; (Hebrews 12:23).  They worship God (Rev. 4:10) and inhabit His heavenly dwelling places (John 14:2) In the Eucharist we come &quot;to the city of the living God&quot; and join in communion with the saints in our worship of God (Heb 12:22)  They are that great &quot;cloud of witnesses&quot; which surrounds us, and we seek to imitate them in running &quot;the race that is set before us&quot; (Heb 12:1)<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
I don't believe prayers are for their salvation, but rather they are prayers seeking intercession on our behalf.  I'm sure <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>JefftheFinn</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> can provide a better answer on this one... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jeffthefinn>jeffthefinn</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://webpages.charter.net/nilus/finnbutton.GIF" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style=color:green;><b>Your Friendly<br>Orthodox Resource</b></span></span><br>  Posts: 182<br> <font color=#B87333>(11/7/03 9:24 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=56.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://webpages.charter.net/nilus/jfinn.JPG WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Praying for the dead</span><hr size=1> God is eternal, and the Eternal is always present.  When we pray for the dead, He who answers prayer is always present, so what we pray now, has an effect in the past.  I know that in Quantum Mechanic Physics there are particles that go back in time.  Our view of time is not what Our Lord sees, and if we limit ourselves to our limited view then prayers for the dead do not seem effective, but that does not mean that they are not.  When I am at Liturgy the whole church is present, past present and future are all there in offering the worship and praise of thanksgiving.<br>
