Where's the Biblical basis for that? <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center">**********************************************<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;Elves seldom give unguarded advice, for advice is a dangerous gift, even from the wise to the wise, and all courses may run ill.&quot; - Gildor (LOTR: FOTR)</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#DEB887><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jeffthefinn>jeffthefinn</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://webpages.charter.net/nilus/finnbutton.GIF" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style=color:green;><b>Your Friendly<br>Orthodox Resource</b></span></span><br>  Posts: 183<br> <font color=#B87333>(11/7/03 7:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=56.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://webpages.charter.net/nilus/jfinn.JPG WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Praying for the dead</span><hr size=1> A good question is what is the past?  Is the past only the viewpoint of the historians?  Do we know everything about the past, do we know everything about everyone or even one person in the present?  I would not limit God, by our own lack of knowing.<br>
Below is an passage of Met. ANTHONY'S (Bloom) book <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Living Prayer</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->.<br>
<!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="font-family:georgia;font-size:small;">&quot;'Many are dismayed at the thought of praying for the dead. Can the destiny of the dead be changed if one prays for them?'<br>
If you believe that prayers for the living are a help to them, why should you not pray for the dead? Life is one, for as St. Luke says: &quot;He is not the God of the dead but of the living&quot;(20:38). Death is not the end but a stage in the destiny of man, and this destiny is not petrified at the moment of death. The love which our prayer expresses cannot be in vain; if love had power on earth and had no power after death it would tragically contradict the word of scripture that love is as strong as death (Song 8: 6) and the experience of the Church that love is more powerful than death, because Christ has defeated death in his love for mankind.<br>
<br>
It is an error to think that man s connection with love on earth ends with his death. In the course of one’s life one sows seeds. These seeds develop in the souls of other men and affect their destiny. The words written or spoken that change a human life or the destiny of mankind, as the words of preachers, philosophers, poets, or politicians, remain their authors responsibility, not only for evil but also for good; the authors destiny is bound to be affected by the way they have influenced those living after them. The life of every person continues to have repercussions until the last judgement, and man’s eternal and final destiny is determined not only by the short space of time he has lived on this earth but also by the results of his life by its good or evil consequences. Those who have received seed sown as in fertile ground, can influence the destiny of the departed by prayerfully beseeching God to bless the man who has transformed their lives, given a meaning to their existence. In turning to God in an act of enduring love, faithfulness and gratitude, they enter this eternal kingdom which transcends the limits of time, and they can influence the destiny and the situation of the departed. We do ask him merely to forgive a man in spite of what he has done but to bless him BECAUSE OF THE GOOD HE HAS DONE, to which other lives bear witness.</span><!--EZCODE FONT END--><br>
Jeff the Finn <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://s88610834.onlinehome.us/Orthodox/index.html" target="top"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://s88610834.onlinehome.us/skunks.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></a><!--EZCODE LINK END--></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jeffthefinn>jeffthefinn</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://webpages.charter.net/nilus/finnbutton.GIF" BORDER=0> at: 11/7/03 9:36 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=peaches116>peaches116</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style=color:green;><b>Dream Writer<br>40 pts.</b></span></span><br>  Posts: 621<br> <font color=#B87333>(11/7/03 8:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=56.topic&index=6>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.onerefuge.com/stitch.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Praying for the dead</span><hr size=1> Why the big writing?  I find it harder to read actually.  It makes me feel you're shouting at me.<br>
<br>
I still see no Biblical references to support your view that our prayers can change the past.<br>
<br>
I don't like this idea at all.  Sure, I've made plenty of mistakes in life, but if I could undo them, I wouldn't.  And I would never ask God to do so because I know God allowed the mistakes of my past and the mistakes others have made to teach me.  And from that learning, I have grown to a deeper understanding of God and a deeper love for Him that I could have never have without all those mistakes.<br>
<br>
And I would never pray for God to erase the mistakes others have made, I would not dare to even wish such a thing upon them.  For it is by making mistakes that either builds our character or breaks us if we are unwilling to learn from the mistakes.  It's our choice on how we deal with our mistakes.  Maturity comes from making mistakes and learning from them.  Maturity can't come if we never make mistakes.  We'd be eternally infants.  And that's why God willed the fall of man.  That's why He willed us to make mistakes.  Not so He could undo them, but so we would learn and would grown out of infanthood into a mature, adult love with Him.  There's a reason why God has sanctified marriage - it is the physical mirror of His love for us in the spiritual.  It's a demonstration of how intense His love for us is and the intense love He wants in return.  It's something we could never offer Him until we made mistakes, learned from them and matured.<br>
<br>
God's not about to change the past.  Nothing happens apart from His will.  For Him to change the past is to say He makes mistakes.  And He makes no mistakes.  Every mistake we make is in His plan.  He knew we'd make it long before we made it and He could have stopped us if that was His will.  But His will was to allow us to make mistakes.  He wants us to leave infanthood behind and grow to a mature relationship with Him.  If He wanted us to remain infants, He'd have never let Adam and Eve sin.  Because of what you suggest, you should just be praying for Him to go back and stop Adam and Eve and that would fix all our mistakes.<br>
<br>
But that is not God's plan for mankind, and so He won't ever change the past.<br>
<br>
And Revelation says that Jesus in eternity looked like a slain Lamb.  The marks of what happened to Him on earth will remain forever, an eternal reminder to us of what He did for us.  But if we forgot about what He saved us from, we would forget what those marks meant and that would be disgraceful to Jesus for us to forget. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center">**********************************************<br>
