<br>
AFAIK, nobody comes near the obsession with prayers for<br>
the dead that the Mormons do. <br>
Among other things, they perform baptisms in proxy for<br>
people who are dead &quot;to save them&quot;.  That's why they're so<br>
obsessed with finding every member of their family tree-<br>
to make sure they were all baptized, one way or another.<br>
============================<br>
Myself, I was raised Catholic. <br>
I can't say what the current Catholic stance on doctrines is,<br>
but I can mention a few things I learned growing up.<br>
<br>
Just as November 1 became &quot;All Saints Day&quot; to commemorate<br>
all the &quot;saints&quot; (the elite Christians, so to speak),<br>
November 2 became &quot;All Souls Day&quot;, to commemorate <br>
everybody else who died.  There is a society extant who <br>
WILL offer prayers for you after death. (I forgot the name.)<br>
I DO know that prayers of various kinds are still being offered<br>
for the dead.<br>
Now, as to why Catholics do it, that I can tell you. The <br>
prayers are for the souls dead and in purgatory. The idea is<br>
that once their sins are expiated, they will pass from <br>
purgatory to heaven.<br>
At this point, I don't agree with this for several reasons.<br>
Mainly two reasons I can cite briefly: either Christ was the<br>
FULL price for our sins, or he wasn't. I say he WAS, so I <br>
don't see the need for a place to do &quot;work-release&quot; to <br>
arrange parole.  The other reason is that I am unable to find<br>
purgatory in the Bible. &quot;Nevertheless, it is one of the <br>
cornerstones of the faith.&quot;  (Not mine, but theirs.)<br>
<br>
If you ever see that video about the life of Martin Luther and<br>
why the Protestant Reformation was started, you'll see a<br>
scene that's not an exaggeration: <br>
a known con man-but EXPERT moneyraiser-<br>
was contracted by the church to raise revenues by the<br>
&quot;selling of indulgences&quot;, that is, the paying off of money to<br>
buy off sins-your own or those of others.<br>
(Indulgences were also granted for pilgrimages to Jerusalem,<br>
participating in a Crusade, and other Acts of the Faith.)<br>
This measure seemed to be the straw that broke the camel's<br>
back for Luther.  The rough translation of the indulgenceman's<br>
slogan runs &quot;the moment the money in the box clinks, the<br>
soul from purgatory springs&quot;.  This was mentioned in Luther's<br>
95 theses at Wittenburg.<br>
<br>
The doctrine of purgatory and indulgences is still active.<br>
I saw an episode of Sister Angelica (a nun who has a program<br>
on the Catholic channel). She was addressing the question<br>
posed by someone suffering chronic pain.  She said some<br>
things I don't want to get into, then also suggested the <br>
person offer up the suffering for the sake of the souls in<br>
purgatory, to put the suffering to end the suffering of others,<br>
so to speak.   <br>
===========================================<br>
(Go ahead, call me an apostate if it makes you feel better.<br>
 Perhaps the suffering will help me shorten my own time.) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/bsparrowshearth.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jeffthefinn>jeffthefinn</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://webpages.charter.net/nilus/finnbutton.GIF" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle><span style=color:green;><b>Your Friendly<br>Orthodox Resource</b></span></span><br>  Posts: 187<br> <font color=#B87333>(11/8/03 2:42 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/fsparrowshearthfrm7.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=56.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://webpages.charter.net/nilus/jfinn.JPG WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Praying for the dead</span><hr size=1> So when someone dies your love for them stops, and their love for you stops?  What does that say about the Resurrection?  Is there such a thing as &quot;dead in Christ&quot;?<br>
